          "body": "Verses 9-11 are one of the New Testament's clearest Trinitarian moments. The **Son** is baptized; the **Spirit** descends like a dove; the **Father** speaks from heaven, *You are My beloved Son, in You I am well-pleased.* The Father's words fuse Psalm 2:7 (the messianic king) with Isaiah 42:1 (the suffering Servant) — Jesus' identity as both royal Son and obedient Servant is fixed at the outset. The Spirit who descends immediately *drives* (*ekballei*) Him into the wilderness — the same verb Jesus will use to drive out demons. The forty days of testing recapitulate Israel's forty years; where Israel failed, the second and faithful Adam prevails. Mark's brevity here is striking — no temptation dialogue, only the bare fact that Jesus was tested, was with wild beasts, and was ministered to by angels (cf. Genesis 2 imagery — Adam and the animals)."
